                "tool_call_id": "call2660cb14cb2a411aa345686eb5c27a11",
                "content": "Computer Vision: Homework 1\nDue on November 6, 2025 at 23:59\nFall 2025\n1\n\nComputer Vision (Fall 2025 ): Homework 1\nProblem 1\nGuidelines\nOnly basic Python, Numpy, and OpenCV functions are allowed, unless otherwise specified. This rule applies\nin particular with the use of OpenCV. Basic image IO functions such as cv2.imread, cv2.imwrite etc. are\nallowed. If you are unsure of an allowable function, please ask TA before assuming. You will get no credit\nfor using a “magic” function to answer any questions where you should be answering them.\nPlease use python 3 for the programming problems. You will be provided with template Python files con-\ntaining functions for you to complete. You can implement your own helper functions if necessary. However,\ndo NOT change the input and output signature of the original functions in the instructions. For all functions\nthat take or return images, make sure to handle the actual arrays. In terms of grading, we would not like\nto judge students by how good the programming results are. Our purpose is to help the students to learn\nmore from the homework, so do not be afraid of your programming results. As long as you’re serious about\nit, we will give you a fair grade.\nWritten Assignment\nConsider a pinhole camera with perspective projection.\na. (15 points) Consider a circular disk that lies in a plane parallel to the image plane. The disk does not\nnecessarily lie on the optical axis. What is the shape of the image of the disk? Show your work and\nderive your equations.\nb. (15 points) In class, we discussed how to find the vanishing point of lines. Suppose I now consider a\nfamily of lines that all lie in a single plane. Where on the image would the vanishing points of ALL\nlines on the plane Ax + By + Cz + D = 0 lie? The coordinate frame is located at the pinhole with the\nz-axis pointing towards the image and the effective focal length is f.\nFirst, start with a simple case where A = C = D = 0 and B = 1 which defines a plane extending\nhorizontally from the optical center. Write down three different line directions in this plane and work\nout where they vanish. Include your work in your submission.\nSecond, do the same with the plane B = C = D = 0 and A = 1. Again include your work in your\nsubmission.\nc. (10 points) Now try to define a general relationship that relates the parameters of the plane to the\nparameters of the vanishing points of all lines that fall in that plane.\nProgramming Assignment\n!!! Include design choices and output images in your write-up (put in the same .pdf file with\nyour written assignment):\n(1) For each required function, list the main ideas behind your code and the choices you made.\n(2) For each required function, if the output is an image, include it in your write-up; if it is a number or a\nshort array, report it in your write-up; if it is a long array (> 10 elements), report the first 10 elements\nin your write-up.\n(3) Please keep your report clear but brief. It should not be more than three pages.\n2\n\nComputer Vision (Fall 2025 ): Homework 1\nProblem 1\nYour task is to implement the core components of the SIFT algorithm to detect stable keypoints\nand compute their local descriptors. You will work on the file h1 sift.py. Please load the image (e.g.,\nexample.jpg) and call your functions. You may NOT use OpenCV’s cv2.SIFT create() or any built-in\nSIFT implementation. However, you may use OpenCV for image I/O, Gaussian blur, and visualization.\na. (20 points) Detect Difference-of-Gaussian (DoG) extrema\nImplement a function that builds a Gaussian pyramid, computes DoG images, and detects scale-space\nextrema:\n1 def\ndetect_dog_keypoints (image , sigma =1.6 ,\nnum_octaves =4, num_scales =3,\ncontrast_thresh =0.03\nedge_r\n=10.0):\n2\n# TODO\n3\nreturn\nkeypoints\n# list of (x, y, sigma)\nListing 1: Function Keypoints\nProcedure:\n• Convert the image to grayscale float32 in [0, 1].\n• Build a Gaussian pyramid with σo,i = σ · 2o · ki, where k = 21/s and s = num scales.\n• Compute the Difference-of-Gaussian (DoG) images between consecutive scales.\n• For each DoG image (except the first and last scale in each octave), find local extrema in a 3×3×3\nneighborhood across scales.\n• Discard points with |D(x)| < contrast thresh or with high edge response.\nOutput: List of (x, y, σ), where (x, y) can be integer or subpixel-approximated.\nb. (20 points) Assign dominant orientation(s) to each keypoint\nFor each keypoint, determine one or more dominant orientations to ensure rotation invariance:\n1 def\ncompute_keypoint_orientation (image , keypoints , sigma_base =1.6\nsigma_ori_mul =1.5, num_bins =36):\n2\n# TODO\n3\nreturn\noriented_keypoints\n# list of (x, y, sigma , theta)\nListing 2: Function Orientation\nProcedure:\n• For each (x, y, σ), compute image gradients in a local window of radius 3σ.\n• Weight gradient magnitudes by a Gaussian with σori = 1.5σ.\n• Build a 36-bin orientation histogram over [0, 2π) and smooth it.\n• The highest peak gives the dominant orientation; create additional keypoints for peaks above 80%\nof the maximum.\nOutput: List of (x, y, σ, θ), where θ is in radians.\nc. (20 points) Compute 128-dimensional SIFT descriptor\nCompute a rotation- and scale-invariant descriptor for each oriented keypoint:\n3\n\nComputer Vision (Fall 2025 ): Homework 1\nProblem 1\n1 def\ncompute_sift_descriptor (image , oriented_keypoints , sigma_base =1.6 ,\ngrid_size =4, bin_per_cell =8):\n2\n# TODO\n3\nreturn\ndescriptors\n# numpy\narray of shape (N, 128)\nListing 3: Function Descriptor\nProcedure:\n• For each keypoint (x, y, σ, θ), sample a 16 × 16 region (scaled by σ) centered at (x, y).\n• For each pixel, compute gradient magnitude and orientation (subtract θ to align).\n• Weight magnitudes by a Gaussian window centered at the keypoint.\n• Divide the region into 4×4 subregions; each subregion forms an 8-bin orientation histogram using\ntrilinear interpolation (spatial + orientation).\n• Concatenate all histograms into a 128-D vector.\n• Normalize to unit length, clamp values above 0.2, and re-normalize.\nOutput: A (N, 128) numpy array, where each row corresponds to one keypoint descriptor.\n4",
